article.description:
Outhustled in the first half, the Phoenix Suns
were challenged by their coach at halftime.
article.headline: Marbury sparks Suns in pivotal third quarter
article.linkText: Suns rally to snap road losing streak in Denver
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Outhustled in the first half, the Phoenix Suns were challenged by their coach at halftime.
Marbury

"I told our guys, 'Play with energy and we can win this game,''' coach Frank Johnson said. "And that's what we did the third quarter. Stephon Marbury scored 19 points, including 10 in the pivotal third quarter, and the Suns defeated the Denver Nuggets 75-72 on Wednesday night. The Suns outscored the Nuggets 29-11 in the third quarter, erasing a nine-point halftime deficit and taking a nine-point lead into the final period. The third-quarter outburst included a 20-3 run highlighted by eight points from Marbury. "We came out and played defense, we got a few more loose balls and we got a little more competitive on the boards,'' Johnson said. Shawn Marion's slam dunk on an alley-oop pass from Marbury made it 49-49 with 5:12 left in the third quarter, and Casey Jacobsen scored the last five points in the spurt, capped by a 3-pointer, for a 55-49 lead. Amare Stoudemire's 31-foot 3-pointer beat the buzzer, giving Phoenix a 62-53 lead. Phoenix shot 63 percent (12 of 19) in the third quarter compared to Denver's 14 percent (2 of 14). The Nuggets failed to score a field goal in the period after Mark Blount's basket with 10:41 left. Juwan Howard scored six straight points early in the fourth quarter as Denver cut the deficit to three points, 66-63. Howard's three-point play made it 71-70 with 1:03 left, but Phoenix hung on. Marion and Marbury each hit two free throws in the final 16.5 seconds. "We are a lot better defensively than we let on,'' Marbury said. "This team can win games with defense when our shots aren't falling.'' Marion said the Nuggets "clearly outhustled us in the first half. They were killing us on the boards. We buckled down in the third quarter and came out aggressive. We worked hard to limit their shots and their rebounds. It was our game then.'' Marion added 14 points and nine rebounds for Phoenix, which won its third straight. Howard led Denver with 19 points. Rookie Nene Hilario had 14 points and 10 rebounds. Denver shot just 33 percent for the game, including 0-for-6 from 3-point range, compared to Phoenix's 39 percent. "If we could shoot, we would be dangerous,'' Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik said. Denver point guard Chris Whitney did not play because of a sprained left ankle. Whitney was injured Nov. 5 but played the last two games. "We really missed Chris tonight, but you deal with the hand you are dealt,'' Bzdelik said. "We are asking a lot of an undrafted rookie (Junior Harrington), especially when it comes to guarding Marbury.'' Added Bzdelik, whose team is the youngest in the NBA, "We are going to be really good someday.'' The Suns used a 7-0 run, capped by Marbury's 3-pointer, to open a 13-6 lead midway through the opening quarter. Hilario scored six of Denver's last eight points in the period as the Nuggets rallied for a 20-19 lead. Stoudemire's short baseline jumper put Phoenix ahead 27-25 early in the second period, but Denver outscored the Suns 17-6 the remainder of the quarter to take a 42-33 halftime lead. Blount scored four points during a 7-0 flurry late in the period. Denver outrebounded Phoenix 29-12 in the half and outshot the Suns 40 percent to 33 percent. Game notes
The Suns snapped an eight-game road losing streak dating to last season. ... Phoenix assistant Mike D'Antoni was the Nuggets head coach in 1998-99 and was Denver rookie Nikoloz Tskitishvili's coach at Benetton Treviso in Italy last season. ... Denver won the season series with the Suns last season (3-1) for the first time in six years. ... It was a matchup of the two lowest-scoring teams in the NBA and second- and third-best defensive teams.
